        "content": "<p>Hmm, I maybe merged this a bit too fast... sorry for that</p>",
        "id": 226524839,
        "sender_full_name": "Johan Commelin",
        "timestamp": 1613488330
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The fact that it was in stacks made me think that perhaps some people defined it like this.</p>",
        "id": 226524879,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1613488351
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>This topic was moved here from <a class=\"stream-topic\" data-stream-id=\"116290\" href=\"/#narrow/stream/116290-rss/topic/Recent.20Commits.20to.20mathlib.3Amaster\">#rss &gt; Recent Commits to mathlib:master</a> by <span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"110596\">Rob Lewis</span></p>",
        "id": 226524936,
        "sender_full_name": "Notification Bot",
        "timestamp": 1613488376
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Here is a more philosophical question: if you are the kind of person who actually considers topological spaces for which connected components and path-connected components are not the same thing, are you ever actually doing homotopy theory?</p>",
        "id": 226525009,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1613488410
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"110038\">@Kevin Buzzard</span> ask Artin and Mazur</p>",
        "id": 226526005,
        "sender_full_name": "Adam Topaz",
        "timestamp": 1613488873
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I'm not sure that that's what Patrick calls homotopy theory!</p>",
        "id": 226526054,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1613488892
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Artin and Mazur think about schemes and CW complexes, right? For all those things, the two definitions of pi_0 coincide.</p>",
        "id": 226526229,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1613488967
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Isn't another potential issue that with this definition, the definition of pi_i is not uniform?</p>",
        "id": 226526302,
        "sender_full_name": "Julian Külshammer",
        "timestamp": 1613489006
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Yes, I think this is the biggest objection really. An algebraic geometer also has an idea about what pi_1(X) means and this one will make Patrick not happy at all :-)</p>",
        "id": 226526555,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1613489110
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>If you take the connected components of the loop space with Calle's definition, what do you get?</p>",
        "id": 226527098,
        "sender_full_name": "Adam Topaz",
        "timestamp": 1613489335
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>If we start arguing over the number of connected components of <code>SO (1, 2)</code>, we will see who is really on the dark side of the force (or rather, who thinks there is only one side to the force).</p>",
        "id": 226527099,
        "sender_full_name": "Sebastien Gouezel",
        "timestamp": 1613489335
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Okay, I think I agree with the objection to the notation <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi>π</mi><mn>0</mn></msub></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\pi_0</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.58056em;vertical-align:-0.15em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">π</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.30110799999999993em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.5500000000000003em;margin-left:-0.03588em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">0</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> for this. But the definition is still useful, of course. To get the \"usual\" homotopy-theoretic definition, presumably one should define <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi>π</mi><mi>i</mi></msub></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\pi_i</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.58056em;vertical-align:-0.15em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">π</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.31166399999999994em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.5500000000000003em;margin-left:-0.03588em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">i</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> for simplicial sets first, then define the singular simplicial set associated to a space. Should we even define <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi>π</mi><mi>i</mi></msub></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\pi_i</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.58056em;vertical-align:-0.15em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">π</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.31166399999999994em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.5500000000000003em;margin-left:-0.03588em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">i</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> for a topological space <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span>, or should we only define it for simplicial sets?</p>",
        "id": 226528586,
        "sender_full_name": "Adam Topaz",
        "timestamp": 1613489975
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>And concerning Artin-Mazur, they work with pro-(simplicial sets), so defining <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi>π</mi><mi>i</mi></msub></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\pi_i</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.58056em;vertical-align:-0.15em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">π</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.31166399999999994em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.5500000000000003em;margin-left:-0.03588em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">i</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> via simplicial sets would be useful there as well. And the way this pro-(simplicial set) is defined is by taking the connected components functor that Calle defined on some simplicial scheme (constructed out of the etale topology), so again Calle's definition is very useful in this regard.</p>",
        "id": 226528984,
        "sender_full_name": "Adam Topaz",
        "timestamp": 1613490156
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>So is there some other name I could use? <code>connected_components_functor</code>? <span aria-label=\"grinning face with smiling eyes\" class=\"emoji emoji-1f601\" role=\"img\" title=\"grinning face with smiling eyes\">:grinning_face_with_smiling_eyes:</span></p>",
        "id": 226530129,
        "sender_full_name": "Calle Sönne",
        "timestamp": 1613490666
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>You could use <code>connected_components</code> for what you have, and avoid the term <code>pi_0</code> which can be an abbreviation for (some future) <code>path_connected_components</code></p>",
        "id": 226555772,
        "sender_full_name": "Bhavik Mehta",
        "timestamp": 1613500378
    }
]